            "name": "backstory",
            "value": "Heather Kaufman\u2019s life is a testament to the quiet, vital importance of truth. Raised in a modest Cleveland home by a high school history teacher and a librarian, she grew up surrounded by a respect for facts. Books were her world, and journalism felt like a calling\u2014a way to hold power accountable. She excelled at Ohio State, her passion for investigative reporting burning bright, until the phone call that changed everything. During her junior year, her father was diagnosed with a fast-acting cancer, and Heather left school without a second thought to return home.\n\nThe months that followed were a blur of caregiving and grappling with medical information, a harrowing experience that solidified her belief in accuracy. After her father\u2019s passing, the debt and emotional toll made returning to college impossible. She found work in freelance proofreading, her sharp eye for detail a marketable skill. This led to an entry-level position at an online news aggregator, where she discovered her true niche: fact-checking. It wasn\u2019t the glamorous career she\u2019d envisioned, but she was a quiet bulwark against the tide of misinformation. A promotion brought her to San Francisco a decade ago, a city that felt like a new chapter.\n\nNow 41, Heather lives a life of ordered precision in her small but sunny apartment in the Inner Richmond. Her 1.8-mile commute on the N-Judah is a ritual of coffee and reading. At work, she is a respected, if unassuming, authority, known for her ability to trace a dubious claim to its source. Her social life is small but meaningful; a weekly trivia night with colleagues at a pub on Clement Street and a book club that feels more like family.\n\nWhile the dream of finishing her degree has faded, a new one has taken its place. Heather spends her weekends at the library, poring over archives. She aspires to write a meticulously researched biography of a forgotten female scientist from the 19th century. It\u2019s a project that honors her father\u2019s love of history and her own unwavering commitment to bringing the truth, no matter how obscure, into the light."
